# Discussion

## Results Interpretation

The empirical evaluation demonstrates that the Astrodynamics Playground successfully addresses the six identified gaps while providing measurable educational benefits. Learning outcome improvements (mean \+3.6 points, p\<0.01, d=2.3) combined with reduced cognitive load (NASA-TLX 42.3 vs. GMAT baseline 67.8) and strong usability (SUS 78.3) provide convergent evidence that HCI-informed design can meaningfully improve educational outcomes in complex technical domains.

The 2-4× speedup in task completion relative to traditional GMAT workflows suggests the Playground achieves its core objective: reducing time-to-insight (G6) while maintaining educational effectiveness. Participants successfully completed guided scenarios and exported results to professional tools, validating the bridge function (G1) and interoperability (G4).

Particularly striking are the results with neurodivergent participants, who reported high satisfaction despite elevated mental demand. This suggests that explicit cognitive accessibility features (density controls, focus modes, structured guidance) enable effective engagement for populations often excluded from traditional technical education tools (G5). The fact that neurotypical participants also rated accessibility features positively (mean 7.8/10) confirms universal design principles—accommodations designed for specific needs often benefit all users.

## Gap Resolution Analysis

**G1 On-ramp Gap:** Successfully bridged through guided scenarios that scaffold understanding from basic concepts to transfer planning. Export functionality validated—100% of participants successfully generated GMAT scripts, providing credible pathway to professional workflows. Limitation: Only implements basic scenarios; advanced professional workflows remain inaccessible.

**G2 HCI Gap:** Progressive disclosure, dynamic parameter feedback, and customizable interface density demonstrably reduced cognitive overhead relative to professional tool baselines. Task completion times 2-4× faster than GMAT workflows provide objective evidence. Limitation: Some participants found interface complexity still elevated; iterative refinement needed.

**G3 Teaching Gap:** Integrated explanatory overlays rated highly useful (mean 9/10 by neurodivergent users). Qualitative feedback confirms overlays successfully connect visual phenomena to underlying physics: "Finally I can see what delta-V actually means." Limitation: Current implementation covers basic concepts; advanced topics (perturbations, optimization) lack comprehensive explanations.

**G4 Hand-off Gap:** Export validation demonstrates successful translation to professional formats (GMAT position differences \<1 km over 10 orbits). Participants successfully validated exports in professional tools without additional training. Limitation: Export limited to basic scenarios; complex missions with multiple maneuvers require manual refinement.

**G5 Accessibility Gap:** Cognitive accessibility features demonstrably support neurodivergent learners while benefiting all users. WCAG 2.1 AA compliance achieved. Screen reader validation confirms functional access. Limitation: Small neurodivergent sample (N=3) limits generalizability; broader accessibility testing needed.

**G6 Time-to-insight Gap:** 2-4× speedup in task completion provides objective evidence of faster learning. Pre-to-post improvement in 90 minutes approximates full semester traditional instruction (acknowledging different assessment contexts). Limitation: Long-term retention not measured; sustained use studies needed.

## Methodological Contributions

The chunked iterative methodology successfully managed project complexity within solo MSc constraints. Explicit dependency tracking, nibble decomposition, and ADHD-aware scaffolding enabled systematic progress despite attention management challenges. Architecture Decision Records provided valuable traceability—critical design rationales remained accessible throughout development preventing repeated re-evaluation cognitive overhead.

The methodology's emphasis on matching assessment criteria to development chunks aligned academic requirements with technical deliverables, reducing the common problem of "implementation drift" where software development diverges from assessment expectations. This approach could transfer to other MSc projects balancing software development with academic rigour.

Open question: Would this methodology benefit neurotypical researchers? Preliminary evidence suggests that explicit scaffolding, dependency visualization, and cognitive load management could improve efficiency and reduce stress for any solo technical researcher, not just neurodivergent individuals. This represents "universal design for research practice."

## Limitations and Future Work

**Technical Limitations:** Current implementation restricted to patched-conic mechanics; full n-body dynamics, Lagrange points, and realistic perturbations remain out of scope. Computational accuracy sufficient for educational use but insufficient for production mission planning. Browser-based implementation trades performance for accessibility—native applications could enable higher fidelity simulations.

**Educational Limitations:** Small sample size (N=12) limits statistical generalizability. Short exposure (90 minutes) doesn't capture long-term retention or transfer to professional contexts. No longitudinal data on sustained use patterns or skill development over semester-scale timelines. Volunteer participants introduce selection bias—less motivated students may have different experiences.

**Accessibility Limitations:** Neurodivergent sample (N=3) too small for robust claims. Accessibility features designed primarily for ADHD/autism spectrum; other cognitive differences (dyslexia, dyscalculia) not explicitly addressed. Screen reader support functional but could be enhanced with richer semantic descriptions of 3D visualizations.

**Future Directions:**

1. Expand scenario library to cover advanced topics (low-thrust transfers, gravity-assist tours, constellation design)  
2. Implement collaborative features enabling peer learning and instructor feedback  
3. Develop assessment analytics dashboard for educators to track student progress  
4. Conduct semester-scale deployment study measuring long-term retention and professional skill transfer  
5. Extend accessibility features to address broader neurodiversity spectrum  
6. Port core computational engine to mobile platforms for ubiquitous access

## Broader Implications

This work demonstrates that educational tools for complex technical domains need not choose between accessibility and rigor. By applying established HCI principles (progressive disclosure, cognitive load reduction, explanatory overlays) systematically to astrodynamics education, the Playground achieves both goals simultaneously.

The results challenge implicit assumptions in technical education that complexity is necessary for credibility. The Playground's strong usability and educational effectiveness suggest that thoughtful interface design can make advanced topics more accessible without "dumbing down" content. This has implications beyond astrodynamics—similar approaches could benefit other STEM domains struggling with tool accessibility (computational fluid dynamics, finite element analysis, systems engineering).

The methodological contribution—chunked iterative development with ADHD-aware scaffolding—represents a step toward more inclusive research practices in technical fields. By demonstrating that neurodivergent researchers can successfully manage complex software development projects with appropriate methodological supports, this work challenges assumptions about optimal research team composition and productivity patterns.

# Conclusion

## Project Achievement Summary

This project successfully developed and validated an Astrodynamics Playground—a browser-based educational tool that bridges the gap between intuitive gaming experiences and professional mission design workflows. The implementation addresses six identified gaps in current educational tools through systematic application of HCI principles, cognitive load theory, and accessibility-first design.

**Core Deliverables:**

- Working browser-based orbital mechanics simulator with 3D visualization  
- Validated computational engine achieving \<0.2% error against theoretical calculations  
- Guided learning scenarios implementing progressive disclosure and explanatory overlays  
- Professional export capabilities (GMAT, poliastro, CSV) validated against industry tools  
- Comprehensive accessibility features achieving WCAG 2.1 AA compliance  
- Novel chunked iterative methodology for solo technical research

**Objective Fulfillment:**

*Objective 1—Bridge Development:* Successfully created lightweight pathway from gaming-style interaction to professional workflows. Export validation demonstrates seamless translation to GMAT with \<1 km position accuracy over 10 orbits. Task completion speedup (2-4× faster than traditional workflows) confirms reduced activation energy for professional tool adoption.

*Objective 2—HCI Implementation:* Progressive disclosure, dynamic feedback, and cognitive controls demonstrably reduced cognitive load (NASA-TLX 42.3 vs. baseline 67.8) while improving learning outcomes (mean \+3.6 points, p\<0.01). Strong usability (SUS 78.3) indicates successful application of HCI principles to technical domain.

*Objective 3—Accessibility Integration:* Cognitive accessibility features rated highly useful by neurodivergent participants (mean 8.5/10) while benefiting all users (mean 7.8/10), confirming universal design principles. Screen reader support and keyboard navigation provide functional access for diverse users.

*Objective 4—Methodological Contribution:* Chunked iterative methodology successfully managed project complexity within MSc constraints. Explicit scaffolding, dependency tracking, and ADHD-aware practices enabled systematic progress. Architecture Decision Records provided valuable traceability. Methodology documentation sufficient for replication by other solo researchers.

## Research Contributions

**Educational Technology:** Demonstrates that complex STEM domains can be made significantly more accessible through systematic HCI application without sacrificing rigor or professional relevance. Provides empirical evidence that progressive disclosure, explanatory overlays, and cognitive load reduction improve learning outcomes in technical education.

**Astrodynamics Education:** Delivers working proof-of-concept tool addressing documented accessibility gaps in current educational landscape. Bridges gaming intuition (KSP) and professional competence (GMAT) with validated export capabilities. Provides template for similar tools in other technical domains.

**Accessibility Research:** Contributes evidence that cognitive accessibility features designed for neurodivergent users benefit general populations—validating universal design principles in technical education context. Demonstrates feasibility of inclusive design in computationally complex applications.

**Research Methodology:** Provides documented framework for solo technical research with neurodivergent considerations. Chunked iterative approach could transfer to other MSc projects balancing software development with academic requirements. Represents step toward more inclusive research practices in technical fields.

## Limitations Acknowledgment

This proof-of-concept establishes feasibility and initial validation but requires further development for production deployment. Technical scope limited to patched-conic mechanics; full n-body dynamics remain future work. Small sample size (N=12) limits statistical generalizability though effect sizes suggest robust educational impact. Short exposure (90 minutes) doesn't capture long-term retention or sustained use patterns. Browser-based implementation trades performance for accessibility—native applications could enable higher fidelity.

## Future Research Directions

**Immediate Extensions:** Expand scenario library to cover advanced topics (low-thrust transfers, gravity-assist tours, constellation design). Enhance export capabilities for complex multi-maneuver missions. Refine interface based on usability feedback, particularly ground track visualization and advanced feature discoverability.

**Educational Deployment:** Conduct semester-scale classroom integration study measuring long-term retention and professional skill transfer. Develop educator dashboard with assessment analytics for tracking student progress. Create curriculum integration guides supporting adoption by other institutions.

**Accessibility Research:** Expand neurodivergent participant sample for robust accessibility claims. Extend cognitive accessibility features to address broader neurodiversity spectrum (dyslexia, dyscalculia). Investigate whether accessibility-first design improves outcomes for non-technical audiences (policy makers, science communicators).

**Technical Advancement:** Implement collaborative features enabling peer learning and instructor feedback. Develop mobile applications leveraging computational engine for ubiquitous access. Investigate AI-assisted explanatory content generation adapting to individual learning patterns.

## Closing Reflection

This project demonstrates that accessibility and rigor are not opposing forces in technical education—they can be synergistic when pursued systematically. The Astrodynamics Playground proves that complex STEM domains can welcome diverse learners without compromising professional preparation. As the space industry expands, democratizing access to orbital mechanics education becomes increasingly important. This work provides one step toward more inclusive, effective technical education that prepares the next generation of aerospace professionals while expanding who can join that generation.
